I hear you.

If “It is done” is meant as the end of a declaration or the conclusion of a piece of writing, then the proclamation has been made within that fictional frame.

If you mean it literally about real people, though, I’d encourage drawing a line between declaring your own path and trying to compel others. You can decide your principles absolutely. You can’t ultimately control whether others accept them, and attempts to force submission often create cycles of conflict that consume the very things a person is trying to protect.

A different kind of finality is:

“It is done. I have chosen my course. My actions will reflect my principles, and others will choose theirs. Time, reality, and consequences will judge us all.”

That keeps the emphasis on your own commitments rather than on dominating other people.

If there’s a larger story, philosophy, or fictional world you’re building, I’m happy to help develop its themes, institutions, or characters in a way that explores power and conviction without encouraging harm in the real world.